<Base
  title="Why Bitter Does Not Build an Agent Harness | Bitter Frontier"
  description="A founder's letter on the 90-tool agent that led to Bitter, the Bitter Lesson, Amdahl's law, and why Frontier tests both ideas in public."
  publishedDate="2026-07-12"
  modifiedDate={modifiedDate}
  articleSection="Bitter Frontier thesis"
  authorName="Michael Ruescher"
  keywords={["Bitter Lesson", "Amdahl's law", "AI agents", "human attention", "coding agent harnesses"]}
>
  <article class="measure py-10">
    <p class="small-caps text-muted">Pinned letter from the founder</p>
    <h1 class="issue-title">An ode to the Bitter Lesson and Amdahl's law maximalism.</h1>
    <p class="profile-dek">
      Why Bitter does not build an agent harness, why human attention is the scarce resource, and why this
      publication exists.
    </p>
    <p class="issue-meta">By Michael Ruescher, founder of Bitter and editor of Bitter Frontier</p>
    <p class="issue-meta">
      Published July 12, 2026. Last revised {modifiedDate}. Living letter.
      <a href={`${GH_REPO_URL}/commits/main/site/src/pages/letter/index.astro`}>Revision history</a>.
    </p>

    <div class="prose-frontier mt-9">
      <p>I built an agent before I built Bitter.</p>

      <p>
        At Blueshift, I built a long-horizon tool-calling agent from scratch. It had compaction, paged tool access, and
        programmatic tool calling. The published architecture covered
        <a href="https://blueshift.com/blog/phasehandoff-long-horizon-agents/">roughly 90 tools and executions across
        millions of tokens</a>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Our <a href="https://blueshift.com/blog/phasehandoff-long-horizon-agents/">first design was a fleet of specialists.
        Nothing failed loudly, but intent quietly evaporated at the handoffs</a>. The system kept producing work while
        the strategy flattened into generic action. We eventually replaced the fleet with a continuous identity that
        moved through phases and left explicit traces for itself.
      </p>

      <p>
        That work taught me the layer I did not want to compete in again.
      </p>

      <p>
        I came away believing that the harness is a punishing layer on which to build a durable company. A provider can
        co-design its model and harness, train against its own interface, observe the combined system at scale, and
        control the inference economics underneath it. A clever independent harness may win locally. The next provider
        release can erase the reason it existed.
      </p>

      <h2 id="bitter-lesson-maxing"><a href="/bitter-lesson/">Bitter Lesson Maxing</a></h2>

      <p>
        Rich Sutton's <a href="http://www.incompleteideas.net/IncIdeas/BitterLesson.html">Bitter Lesson</a> gave me a
        name for the pattern. General methods that improve through computation, learning, and search repeatedly overtake
        handcrafted systems. My business version is simple: build where improving general agents compound your
        advantage, not where their next release erases it. I call that Bitter Lesson Maxing.
      </p>

      <p>
        That is why Bitter does not own a house reasoning loop. Bring Codex, Claude Code, Pi, or the next harness that
        earns your trust. Bitter is betting that agent cognition will become replaceable. The operating environment,
        repository, authority, deployment, logs, customer feedback, and company history should survive the swap.
      </p>

      <h2 id="amdahl-maxing"><a href="/amdahls-law/">Amdahl Maxing</a></h2>

      <p>
        <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/1465482.1465560">Amdahl's law</a> explains the other half. Making one part of a
        workload infinitely fast cannot overcome the fraction that remains serial. In a company full of agents, human
        attention is that scarce serial resource. Faster code generation does not
        make a faster company when prioritization, review, deployment, support, and learning still queue behind the same
        person. More agent output can make the system slower when every artifact returns as an interruption.
      </p>

      <p>
        Amdahl Maxing means designing the enterprise so scarce attention is spent where judgment has the highest
        marginal value: direction, taste, ambiguity, consequential risk, customer evidence, and accountability. Routine
        work should happen inside clear authority, be verified mechanically where possible, and return decision packets
        instead of transcripts.
      </p>

      <p>
        Not every human gate is waste. A deliberate boundary for responsibility or an irreversible action may be the
        point. Re-entering the same state across five tools, approving low-risk actions one at a time, and reviewing
        unfiltered agent output are accidental serial work.
      </p>

      <h2>Why Frontier exists</h2>

      <p>
        Bitter deliberately depends on upstream models and harnesses. We need to understand what they can now do, where
        authority lives, which release contains the change, what state survives, and what new work reaches the human
        queue. Bitter Frontier is that intelligence function made public.
      </p>

      <p>
        A release note describes one provider in isolation. It will not tell you that another project tried the same
        design earlier, that the shared feature name hides different defaults, or that one fix reached stable while the
        other still lives on a branch. Frontier reads projects together and provides cross-project memory no single
        project can supply.
      </p>

      <p>
        The publication asks what agents just made cheaper, what handcrafted layer became less defensible, which part of
        the end-to-end company loop agents can now operate, and where scarce human attention moved next.
      </p>

      <h2>See the thesis meet the evidence</h2>

      <p>
        <a href="/digests/2026-07-01_2026-07-02-weekly/">Foreground Attention Is No Longer the Control</a>
        is the cleanest current Amdahl example. <a href="https://github.com/anthropics/claude-code/releases/tag/v2.1.198">Claude
        Code let background agents commit, push, and open draft pull requests</a>,
        moving human attention from a terminal prompt to repository policy and
        review. <a href="https://github.com/openai/codex/releases/tag/rust-v0.142.5">Codex moved a permission consequence
        into trace retention</a>, while Gemini showed that
        <a href="https://github.com/google-gemini/gemini-cli/releases/tag/v0.51.0-nightly.20260702.gff00dacd9">a fix in
        nightly does not protect a stable operator</a>.
      </p>

      <p>
        The <a href="/profiles/agent-flywheel/">Agent Flywheel profile</a> tests
        the Bitter Lesson from the other direction. Its
        <a href="https://github.com/Dicklesworthstone/agentic_coding_flywheel_setup/blob/v0.7.0/docs/methodology/THE_FLYWHEEL_CORE_LOOP.md">tagged
        method keeps plans, task state, coordination, verification, and memory
        outside any one provider agent</a>. That is bitter-pilled engineering.
        The same review still finds incomplete authority boundaries. Choosing
        the right layer does not excuse weak defaults.
      </p>

      <p>
        The <a href="/bitter-lesson/">Bitter Lesson essay</a> and
        <a href="/amdahls-law/">Amdahl's Law essay</a> collect more cases that support and complicate each part of the bet.
      </p>

      <h2>The line we will not cross</h2>

      <p>
        These ideas determine the questions. They do not predetermine the answers. A specialized method may remain
        valuable. More autonomy may reduce total throughput. A human approval gate may be the correct design. A provider
        change may contradict Bitter's assumptions. Frontier should publish those conclusions when the receipts support
        them.
      </p>

      <p>
        Bitter is the disclosed publisher. It does not become the answer inside the reporting. The publication has to
        remain useful to someone who never becomes a Bitter customer. Trust first, product second.
      </p>

      <h2>A living letter</h2>

      <p>
        This is not a finished doctrine pinned in amber. Models will improve, provider harnesses will absorb new layers,
        Bitter will mature, and our understanding of both constraints will get sharper. I will revise this letter when
        the evidence changes the read. Frontier is where we test the bet in public. If the evidence breaks it, the record
        should show that too.
      </p>

      <p class="founder-signoff">
        Michael Ruescher<br />
        Founder, <a href="https://bitter.sh">Bitter</a><br />
        Editor, Bitter Frontier
      </p>
    </div>

